			8 thoughts on ‚Äú Vision and/or Hype in Search ‚Äù		 

		  
		   Bradley Horowitz    August 30, 2006 at 9:24 pm 			 I‚Äôm here Ramesh! 
 My reaction to those words is one mostly of ‚Äúwhimsy‚Ä¶‚Äù  Remembering fondly the sweet vanities of youth! üòâ  Seriously though, I don‚Äôt feel I‚Äôve abandoned Computer Vision so much as graduated to an expanded perspective.  We were trying to solve through brute force a problem that begged for a socio-technical solution.  I‚Äôm enamored not only of Flickr, but also approaches like Luis von Anh‚Äôs espgame and peekaboom. 
 The joke in my talk is not that I realized Computer Vision is hard and hence we need tagging.  Actually the joke is that most my mentors in the field have themselves ‚Äúdeclared success and moved on.‚Äù  Moved on to grander endeavors like ‚ÄúAffective Computing‚Äù (Roz Picard), ‚ÄúHuman Dynamics‚Äù (Sandy Pentland), and ‚ÄúExperiential Computing‚Äù (see title of this blog.) 
 The truth is that I‚Äôm very much committed to the vision we had at Virage.  Our vision there was always pragmatic ‚Äì by all means possible, including human editorial. 
 It‚Äôs with some measure of chagrin that I note the quote is from Riya.  This company was touted with much fanfare earlier this year as ‚Äúthe Flickr killer.‚Äù  Ummmm‚Ä¶.  Didn‚Äôt happen!  In fact, I‚Äôm not sure Flickr experienced even so much as a noticable ‚Äúblip‚Äù in the wake of Riya‚Äôs launch. 
 Anyway, for me (and for us at Yahoo), it has never been an issue of man v. machine.  It‚Äôs always been a simple equation:  man + machine &gt; machine (alone).  We continue to work on what you‚Äôd know as ‚Äúpure computer vision‚Äù, much more than the outside world might expect (and granted more than we talk about!) 
 I also applaud and commend Munjal‚Äôs work.  I‚Äôm excited about improving the ‚Äúmachine‚Äù aspect of the equation, and there remains a lot of work to be done! 
							 
							 
		 
	 
		  Ramesh   Post author   September 1, 2006 at 5:23 pm 			 Thanks, Bradley. 
 This space is really getting hot.  You must have seen the Google effort in tagging that is being talked about. 
							 
							 
		 
	 
		   Rajan    September 1, 2006 at 10:43 pm 			 Prof,  
       Could‚Äônt help but smile on the pun in the beginning words of your post ‚Äúseperating vision from hype‚Äù . 
     I have a little background in vision and thus can perfectly understand the sentiments that you reflected about the field of vision.  
     Vision is young and one of the hottest field in CS and though a lot of important problems have been solved in it and probably only about small % of key problems in it still needs solution but it is  these small % of the problem which really hinders in  vision making transition from research to technology. 
							 
							 
		 
	 
		  Ramesh   Post author   September 2, 2006 at 12:48 pm 			 Thanks. 
Computer vision can, and hopefully soon will, play important role in many applications.  Image retrieval will be only one of those.  There are some interesting challenges that must be solved in vision for that to happen.   
 Because you caught the pun, did you see ‚ÄòIgnorance, Myopia, and Naivette in Computer Vision‚Äô that appeared in Computer vision, Graphics, and Image processing about 15 years ago? 
							 
							 
		 
	 
		   Munjal shah    October 4, 2006 at 5:39 pm 			 Ramesh and Bradley, 
 You are write.  The hard part about Riya is that when you talk to people about it, their imagination runs wild.  When we launched Riya our registration flow even said it was ‚Äúonly as smart as a two year old.(interms of recognition ability).‚Äù   
 I do however feel that if you narrow your application there are areas that computer vision can succeed in.  I would love for both of you to join our private alpha for Riya‚Äôs next product which will be launched in about a month.  I would love your feedback and advice.  Email me at blog3 at munjal.com 
							 
							 
		 
	 
		   Barney Pell    October 11, 2006 at 2:26 am 			 Ramesh, 
 You are absolutely right that Moore‚Äôs law is only one piece of the problem for bringing AI capabilities into actual products.  The fundamental science has to advance enough as well. I think we are converging in both NLP and Computer Vision over the next 5-10 years sufficient to make large-scale applications that really change things (though I know more about the former than the latter).  
 So far the two technologies have been isolated, but it will be interesting to see what happens when they can work together. For example, a vision system may tag objects, scenes, and relationships, which could then be queried in natural language. 
 I also agree with Bradley that man + machine &gt; machine.  A little bit of human effort can go a long way.  As a slightly otherworldly example, 
there is some interesting work at NASA by Terry Fong in which mobile robots call on humans to solve perceptual subproblems, while the AI controls the overall process. 
							 
							 
		 
	 
